  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "VJ/MsS5k5qIf+UzuHzXG3RP066g=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:30.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Pipeline\n\nThe end-to-end flow inside the browser:\n\n1. **Connect UI (React)** \u2014 user actions (create drive, add doc, edit).\n2. **ReactorClient** \u2014 turns actions into Jobs, enqueues them.\n3. **Job Executor** \u2014 applies operations (`CREATE_DOCUMENT`, `UPGRADE_DOCUMENT`, `ADD_FILE`, `ADD_FOLDER`, `MOVE_NODE`, domain actions).\n4. **PGlite (WASM Postgres, IndexedDB-backed)** \u2014 stores `reactor.Document`, `reactor.Operation`, `reactor.DocumentSnapshot`, `reactor.DocumentRelationship`, plus `operation_index_operations`, `sync_remotes`, `sync_cursors`, `sync_dead_letters`.\n5. **SyncManager** \u2014 detects new ordinals, groups ops by `(docId, scope, branch)`, pushes to channel outboxes, processes inboxes via `reactor.load()`.\n6. **Channels** \u2014 `GqlRequestChannel` for Switchboard, `SwarmChannel` for Swarm. SyncManager treats both identically.\n\nBeyond the browser: the SwarmChannel talks to the user's **Bee node** (`/bytes`, `/feeds`, `/stamps`, `/health`), which gossips chunks into the **Swarm network** (content-addressed, encrypted, replicated across neighborhoods).\n\nKey architectural insight: PGlite's `operation_index_operations` is the single source for both channels' outbound sync, with independent cursors per remote.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:30.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:30.000Z"
    }
  },
